I am implementing an AVL tree in C++ and I'm stuck on the right-left (RL) rotation. My code seems to crash when the rotation happens at the root level. Here is my RL rotation logic:

void rl_rotate(Node* x) {
    Node* y = x->right;
    x->right = y->left;
    if (y->left) y->left->parent = x;
    y->left = x;
    y->parent = x->parent;
    x->parent = y;
    if (root == x) root = y;
}

Could someone tell me why this might be causing a segmentation fault during the height update phase?

I'm having trouble understanding how to handle the height update after a rotation in an AVL tree. I have a function that performs a left rotation, but the balance factor of the nodes doesn't seem to update correctly. Here is the snippet:

void rotateLeft(Node* A) {
    Node* B = A->right;
    A->right = B->left;
    B->left = A;
    A->height = max(height(A->left), height(A->right)) + 1;
    B->height = max(height(B->left), height(B->right)) + 1;
}

Is the order of height updates correct here?

Can someone help me debug my `getBalance` function? I'm getting weird results when a node has a null child. Here is my code:

int getBalance(Node* n) {
    if (n == NULL) return 0;
    return n->left->height - n->right->height;
}

I keep getting a null pointer dereference. How should I properly handle the null children cases?

I am struggling with the single right rotation (LL case) in my AVL tree implementation. I've written the pointer swaps, but I think I'm losing the connection to the parent node. Here is my current implementation:

Node* rightRotate(Node* y) {
    Node* x = y->left;
    Node* T2 = x->right;
    x->right = y;
    y->left = T2;
    return x;
}

How do I integrate this with a parent pointer system so the rest of the tree stays connected?

I have a bug in my AVL tree where the `insert` function doesn't maintain the balance property. I've implemented the rotations, but the height of the nodes isn't being updated correctly during the recursion. If I insert 10, 20, 30, the tree should rotate, but it stays as a linked list. Here is my insert function logic:

Node* insert(Node* node, int key) {
    if (node == NULL) return new Node(key);
    if (key < node->key) node->left = insert(node->left, key);
    else node->right = insert(node->right, key);
    node->height = 1 + max(height(node->left), height(node->right));
    return balance(node);
}

I've implemented the AVL tree insertion, but I'm failing the test cases for the LR rotation. Here is my current logic for the LR case:

Node* lrRotation(Node* node) {
    node->left = leftRotate(node->left);
    return rightRotate(node);
}

Is this the correct way to handle the LR case, or should I be updating the heights of the nodes manually between the two rotations?

I've written a function for the RR rotation in my AVL tree, but it's not working as expected. Here is the code:

void rr_rotate(Node* v) {
    Node* tmp = v->right;
    v->right = tmp->left;
    if (tmp->left) tmp->left->parent = v;
    tmp->left = v;
    tmp->parent = v->parent;
    v->parent = tmp;
    if (root == v) root = tmp;
}

When I run this, the tree becomes disconnected. What am I doing wrong?

I'm implementing an AVL tree from scratch in C++ and I'm struggling with the balance factor updates during a right rotation. Specifically, when I perform the rotation, the height of the rotated subtree seems to be incorrect, which leads to the tree not being balanced after multiple insertions. Here is the snippet where I update heights: 

void rotateRight(Node* &root) {
    Node* L = root->left;
    root->left = L->right;
    L->right = root;
    updateHeight(root);
    updateHeight(L);
}

When I run this on a tree with keys 10, 5, and 2, the height of the node with key 10 becomes 0 instead of 1. I'm not sure why the height isn't propagating correctly. Any ideas?

I'm trying to implement an AVL tree for my data structures course, but my rotations seem to be causing issues with the tree structure. Every time I perform a double rotation, the tree becomes corrupted and I start getting NullPointerExceptions during traversal. I've checked my single rotation logic and it seems fine, but the double rotation is where it fails. Here is my current implementation of the rotation methods:

public AVLNode rotateRight(AVLNode y) {
    AVLNode x = y.left;
    AVLNode T2 = x.right;
    x.right = y;
    y.left = T2;
    updateHeight(y);
    updateHeight(x);
    return x;
}

public AVLNode rotateLeft(AVLNode x) {
    AVLNode y = x.right;
    AVLNode T2 = y.left;
    y.left = x;
    x.right = T2;
    updateHeight(x);
    updateHeight(y);
    return y;
}

public AVLNode doubleRotateRight(AVLNode node) {
    node.left = rotateLeft(node.left);
    return rotateRight(node);
}

public AVLNode doubleRotateLeft(AVLNode node) {
    node.right = rotateRight(node.right);
    return rotateLeft(node);
}

I suspect I am updating the heights in the wrong order or perhaps the pointer assignments in the double rotation are incorrect. How can I fix this?

I am having a strange problem with my AVL tree deletion method. When I delete a node that has two children, the tree doesn't seem to rebalance correctly, and the height of the tree becomes inconsistent. I am using the successor method to replace the deleted node. Could you look at my delete logic and tell me why the balance factor isn't being updated correctly?

protected AVLNode delete(AVLNode root, int key) {
    if (root == null) return root;
    if (key < root.key) root.left = delete(root.left, key);
    else if (key > root.key) root.right = delete(root.right, key);
    else {
        if (root.left == null || root.right == null) {
            root = (root.left == null) ? root.right : root.left;
        } else {
            AVLNode temp = findMin(root.right);
            root.key = temp.key;
            root.right = delete(root.right, temp.key);
        }
    }
    if (root == null) return root;
    root.height = Math.max(height(root.left), height(root.right)) + 1;
    int balance = getBalance(root);
    if (balance > 1 && getBalance(root.left) >= 0) return rotateRight(root);
    if (balance > 1 && getBalance(root.left) < 0) {
        root.left = rotateLeft(root.left);
        return rotateRight(root);
    }
    if (balance < -1 && getBalance(root.right) <= 0) return rotateLeft(root);
    if (balance < -1 && getBalance(root.right) > 0) {
        root.right = rotateRight(root.right);
        return rotateLeft(root);
    }
    return root;
}

I'm struggling with the height calculation in my AVL tree. I've noticed that my tree is not rotating when it should, even though the balance factor exceeds 1. I think the issue is in how I'm calculating the height of the children. I'm using a recursive approach but it's returning 0 for all nodes except the root. Here is my code:

public int getHeight(Node node) {
    if (node == null) return 0;
    return 1 + Math.max(getHeight(node.left), getHeight(node.right));
}

public void insert(int key) {
    root = insertRecursive(root, key);
}

private Node insertRecursive(Node node, int key) {
    if (node == null) return new Node(key);
    if (key < node.key) node.left = insertRecursive(node.left, key);
    else if (key > node.key) node.right = insertRecursive(node.right, key);
    else return node;

    node.height = getHeight(node);
    int balance = getHeight(node.left) - getHeight(node.right);
    // rotation logic here...
    return node;
}

Is there a more efficient way to track height without calling a recursive function every time I insert a node?

My AVL tree implementation is failing some test cases related to the 'Right-Left' case rotation. I'm not sure if I'm calling the rotate functions in the correct sequence. For a Right-Left imbalance, should I rotate the right child to the right first, and then rotate the root to the left? I've tried implementing it like this:

if (balance < -1 && key < root.right.key) {
    root.right = rotateRight(root.right);
    return rotateLeft(root);
}

But the output tree is still not balanced. I'm using Java and the nodes have a height property. Can someone explain the logic for the RL case and check if my sequence is correct?

I am implementing an AVL tree in C++ and I'm having trouble with memory management during rotations. Every time I perform a rotation, I feel like I'm losing pointers to some of my nodes, leading to memory leaks. I am using raw pointers instead of smart pointers. Here is my rotateLeft function:

Node* rotateLeft(Node* x) {
    Node* y = x->right;
    Node* T2 = y->left;
    y->left = x;
    x->right = T2;
    x->height = max(height(x->left), height(x->right)) + 1;
    y->height = max(height(y->left), height(y->right)) + 1;
