}

Could the problem be that I'm not updating the heights of the nodes after the rotation?

I'm trying to implement a method to print the AVL tree in an in-order traversal to verify if it's still a Binary Search Tree after rotations. The output is sorted, but when I print the heights of the nodes, they don't match the actual distance to the leaves. For example, a node with no children has a height of 1, but its parent has a height of 1 as well. This is impossible. I think my updateHeight method is flawed. Here it is:

void updateHeight(Node n) {
    n.height = Math.max(n.left.height, n.right.height) + 1;
}

What happens if n.left or n.right is null? I'm getting a NullPointerException here.

I am implementing an AVL tree in C++ and I'm encountering a segmentation fault during the rotation process. I suspect my pointer updates in the rotateRight function are incorrect. Here is my code:

void rotateRight(Node* &k) {
    Node* x = k->left;
    k->left = x->right;
